            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "I wanted to work on this and here's what I found.\n\n### Investigation\n\nI profiled `cython_inline()` with `cProfile` to see where the time actually goes. Per call:\n\n- C compiler + linker subprocess: ~162ms (irreducible)\n- `cythonize()` (Cython → C): ~19ms\n- `unbound_symbols()`: <3ms (cached)\n- `load_dynamic()`: ~0.3ms\n- `_get_build_extension()`: ~3-6ms\n\nThe compilation cost itself is reasonable. The problem is that it happens every single time the tests run.\n\n### Root cause\n\n`cython_inline()` has an on-disk cache keyed by SHA-256 of the code, arg types, Python version, executable, language level, and `Cython.__version__`. But `TestInline.setUp()` calls `tempfile.mkdtemp()` — a fresh empty directory per test method. The `.so` files from previous runs are abandoned in old temp dirs and never reused. Every test run invokes the C compiler from scratch (~180ms per snippet, ~12 unique snippets).\n\n`test_kwds` also sets `force=True`, but this is dead code here — the temp directory is always empty so `not os.path.isfile(module_path)` is already `True`, and the in-memory `_cython_inline_cache` fast path returns before the `force` check on repeat calls within the same process.\n\nThe `tempfile.mkdtemp()` was added intentionally in 475e9a08 (and reinforced in 72e7dda3) to prevent tests from polluting the user's `~/.cython/inline` directory. So we can't just drop it.\n\n### Proposed fix\n\nUse a stable directory under `tempfile.gettempdir()` (e.g. `/tmp/cython_inline_test_cache`) instead of `tempfile.mkdtemp()`. This preserves test isolation from `$HOME` while allowing the disk cache to work across runs. Also remove `force=True` since it serves no purpose (4 of 12 tests already don't use it and rely on the hash-based cache).\n\n| Scenario | Before | After |\n|---|---|---|\n| Cold (no cached `.so`) | 5.7s | ~2.8s |\n| Warm (cached `.so` on disk) | 5.7s | 0.18s |\n\nHappy to open a PR if this approach looks right.",
